notes.body:
**Template 1 — subsets (include/exclude).** For each element you make a binary decision: take it or skip it. The tree has depth $n$ and $2^n$ leaves, and every leaf is a valid subset.

```cpp
// ---------- TEMPLATE 1: SUBSETS (include/exclude, order doesn't matter) ----------
// For each element you decide to take it or not. 2^n leaves.
void subsets(int i, vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cur, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
    if (i == (int)nums.size()) {           // decided every element
        res.push_back(cur);                // every node/leaf is a valid subset
        return;
    }
    cur.push_back(nums[i]);                 // choice: take nums[i]
    subsets(i + 1, nums, cur, res);
    cur.pop_back();                         // UNDO
    subsets(i + 1, nums, cur, res);         // choice: skip nums[i]
}
```

[[fig:m09-subset-tree]]

> [!EXAMPLE] Trace on `[1,2]`
> take 1 → take 2 → record `[1,2]` → undo 2 → record `[1]` → undo 1 → skip 1 → take 2 → record `[2]` → undo 2 → record `[]`. Four leaves, four subsets, and `cur` is empty again when the function returns — proof the undos balanced.

**Template 2 — combinations (the `start` index).** When order doesn't matter and you loop over choices, you must stop `[2,3]` and `[3,2]` from both appearing. The fix: pass a `start` index and only look **forward**. Each combination is then generated in exactly one (sorted-position) order.

```cpp
// ---------- TEMPLATE 2: COMBINATIONS / COMBINATION-SUM (start index avoids dups) ----------
// Use a `start` index so you never reuse earlier elements -> combinations, not permutations.
void combine(int start, vector<int>& nums, vector<int>& cur, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
    res.push_back(cur);                     // record current combination (if every prefix is valid)
    for (int i = start; i < (int)nums.size(); ++i) {
        cur.push_back(nums[i]);             // choose nums[i]
        combine(i + 1, nums, cur, res);     // i+1 => can't reuse; i => allow reuse (combination sum)
        cur.pop_back();                     // UNDO
    }
}
```

[[fig:m09-start-index]]

> [!KEY] The `i` / `i+1` / `used[]` dial
> Recurse with `i + 1` → each element used at most once (Combinations, Subsets II). Recurse with `i` → the same element may be reused (Combination Sum). Loop from `0` with a `used[]` array → order matters (Permutations). This single decision is the difference between three whole problem families — mixing them up silently produces wrong-shaped output.

> [!NOTE]
> Template 2 records `cur` at **every** node, not just leaves — a subset/combination of any size is an answer. Contrast with permutations below, where only full-length leaves count. Deciding *where the base case records* is part of understanding the problem.

When **order matters**, the `start` index is wrong — `[3,2]` genuinely differs from `[2,3]` and both must appear. So at every level you consider *all* elements, and use a `used[]` array to skip the ones already placed in the current prefix.

```cpp
// ---------- TEMPLATE 3: PERMUTATIONS (order matters, track used) ----------
void permute(vector<int>& nums, vector<bool>& used,
             vector<int>& cur, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
    if (cur.size() == nums.size()) { res.push_back(cur); return; }
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); ++i) {
        if (used[i]) continue;              // pruning: skip already-placed elements
        used[i] = true; cur.push_back(nums[i]);
        permute(nums, used, cur, res);
        cur.pop_back(); used[i] = false;    // UNDO both
    }
}
```

The tree fans out $n$ ways at the root, $n-1$ at the next level, and so on: $n!$ leaves, and copying each answer costs $O(n)$, so the total is $O(n \cdot n!)$.

> [!PITFALL] Undo **both** mutations
> You made two changes — `used[i] = true` *and* `cur.push_back(...)` — so you must undo two. Forgetting `used[i] = false` makes elements vanish from later branches; forgetting `pop_back()` makes `cur` grow past `nums.size()` and the base case never fires cleanly.

> [!INTUITION] Subsets vs permutations in one sentence
> Subsets ask **"which elements?"** (binary decision per element, $2^n$); permutations ask **"which element next?"** (shrinking menu per slot, $n!$). Pick the question the problem is really asking and the template follows.

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive version fails.** If your loop starts from index 0 at every level, you'll generate `[2,3]` and `[3,2]` as *separate* results — you're enumerating permutations, not combinations, and the duplicate explosion buries you.

> [!KEY] The start index enforces one canonical order
> At each recursion level you may only pick candidates from index `i` **onward**. Every combination is then built in exactly one non-decreasing order of positions, so each *set* appears exactly once — no set-based dedup needed.

[[fig:m09-start-index]]

**The reuse trick.** To allow using a number again, recurse with the **same index `i`** (not `i+1`). Read it as: `i` = "I may pick this one more time"; `i+1` = "I'm done with this candidate, move on." One character controls the entire reuse semantics.

**The pruning that wins OAs.** Sort the candidates first. Then inside the loop, the moment `c[i] > target`, every later candidate is even larger — cut the whole tail with `break`, not `continue`.

```cpp
void dfs(int start, int target, vector<int>& c, vector<int>& cur, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
    if (target == 0) { res.push_back(cur); return; }
    for (int i = start; i < (int)c.size(); ++i) {
        if (c[i] > target) break;      // PRUNE: sorted candidates -> the rest are larger too
        cur.push_back(c[i]);
        dfs(i, target - c[i], c, cur, res);  // `i` (not i+1) => reuse allowed
        cur.pop_back();                       // UNDO
    }
}
// caller: sort(c); dfs(0, target, c, cur, res);
```

**Complexity.** Worst case $O(N^{T/M})$ tree nodes, where $T$ = target and $M$ = smallest candidate — depth is bounded by $T/M$ (each pick removes at least $M$ from the target) and each node branches up to $N$ ways. Space is the $O(T/M)$ recursion depth.

**What generalizes.** The `start`-index-plus-sorted-`break` combo is the skeleton for Combination Sum II/III, Subsets II, and every "pick numbers to hit a bound" OA question. Decide `i` vs `i+1` first; add the sorted `break` second; only then think about anything else.

**Why the naive version fails.** Generating all $n!$ permutations and dumping them into a `set` works — but it does exponentially more work than needed and interviewers explicitly want the pruning. The subtlety: with no `start` index, the `i > start` sibling-skip from subsets doesn't apply. You need a different signal for "this choice would repeat a sibling".

> [!INTUITION] Read `used[i-1]` as "where is my twin right now?"
> Sort so equal values are adjacent. About to place `nums[i]` where `nums[i] == nums[i-1]`: if `used[i-1]` is **false**, the identical twin was already tried *and backtracked* at this very depth — choosing `nums[i]` now would rebuild that exact branch. Skip it. If `used[i-1]` is **true**, the twin is part of the *current prefix* (a genuinely different position, one level up), so placing `nums[i]` here is new and legal.

```cpp
sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
void dfs(vector<int>& nums, vector<bool>& used, vector<int>& cur, vector<vector<int>>& res) {
    if (cur.size() == nums.size()) { res.push_back(cur); return; }
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); ++i) {
        if (used[i]) continue;
        if (i > 0 && nums[i] == nums[i-1] && !used[i-1]) continue; // key dedup line
        used[i] = true; cur.push_back(nums[i]);
        dfs(nums, used, cur, res);
        cur.pop_back(); used[i] = false;
    }
}
```

**Walking the logic on `[1,1,2]`.** At the root, `i=0` places the first `1` and its subtree produces `[1,1,2]` and `[1,2,1]`. Back at the root, `i=1` sees `nums[1]==nums[0]` and `used[0]==false` (the first `1` was just undone) → skip, because its subtree would be a carbon copy. `i=2` places `2`, and inside that branch the two `1`s are placed in index order, giving `[2,1,1]`. Three unique permutations, zero wasted subtrees.

**Why not the opposite condition (`used[i-1]`)?** Flipping it also dedups (it just canonicalizes the *reverse* order of twins) but prunes far later — the `!used[i-1]` version kills a duplicate branch at the shallowest possible node, which is where the exponential savings are.

**Complexity.** $O(n \cdot n!)$ worst case (all values distinct — it degrades gracefully to plain permutations); with many duplicates the pruned tree is dramatically smaller, approaching the true count $n!/(k_1!\,k_2!\cdots)$ of distinct permutations.

**What generalizes.** Any "enumerate orderings with repeated items" task — string permutations, arranging tiles — uses exactly this sort + `!used[i-1]` guard.

**Why the naive version fails.** A separate `visited[m][n]` boolean matrix *works*, but it costs $O(mn)$ extra memory and — worse under time pressure — it's easy to desync: forget one `visited[r][c] = false` on backtrack and the search silently misses valid paths.

> [!KEY] The board is its own visited set
> Overwrite the cell with a sentinel `'#'` before recursing, restore the original character after. The sentinel does **double duty**: it can never equal `w[k]`, so the mismatch check automatically stops you from stepping on your own path — no separate visited lookup at all — and restoring it lets sibling search paths reuse the cell.

```cpp
bool dfs(vector<vector<char>>& b, int r, int c, const string& w, int k) {
    if (k == (int)w.size()) return true;                 // matched all chars
    if (r < 0 || c < 0 || r >= (int)b.size() || c >= (int)b[0].size()) return false;
    if (b[r][c] != w[k]) return false;                   // mismatch or already-visited sentinel

    char tmp = b[r][c];
    b[r][c] = '#';                                        // mark visited in place
    bool found = dfs(b,r+1,c,w,k+1) || dfs(b,r-1,c,w,k+1)
              || dfs(b,r,c+1,w,k+1) || dfs(b,r,c-1,w,k+1);
    b[r][c] = tmp;                                        // UNDO — restore the char
    return found;
}
```

Notice the ordering discipline: check the **success** base case *before* the bounds check (the word can end exactly at an edge), and do bounds *before* touching `b[r][c]`. The short-circuit `||` chain also stops exploring the moment any direction succeeds — a free prune.

One more subtlety: `found` is captured *before* the restore, and the restore runs whether the branch succeeded or failed — the mutate/restore pair brackets the recursion unconditionally, which is exactly the make → recurse → undo shape from the notes, applied to a grid cell instead of a vector.

**Complexity.** $O(m \cdot n \cdot 4^L)$ where $L$ = word length: each of the $mn$ start cells spawns a DFS that branches up to 4 ways per character (3 effectively, since you can't immediately go back). Space: $O(L)$ recursion depth — no visited matrix.

**What generalizes.** Mutate-in-place-then-restore is *the* grid-backtracking idiom: Word Search II layers a Trie on top of this exact DFS, and Sudoku Solver applies the same place/undo bracket to digits instead of path cells.

**Why the naive version fails.** For each candidate cell, scanning the column and both diagonals to check safety costs $O(n)$ per check and produces messy code. Two ideas turn this into a clean, fast search.

**Idea 1 — one queen per row.** Since no two queens can share a row, recurse *by row*: `solve(row)` chooses a column for that row's queen. The row constraint is now satisfied by construction — you never even need to check it.

**Idea 2 — diagonals are just index sums and differences.** Every cell on the same ↙ anti-diagonal shares the value `row + col`; every cell on the same ↘ diagonal shares `row - col` (add `n` to keep the index non-negative). So the entire attack check collapses to three boolean-array lookups.

[[fig:m09-nqueens-diag]]

> [!EXAMPLE] Check it on real cells
> (2,3) and (4,1): `row+col` is 5 for both → same ↙ diagonal, they attack. (0,0) and (3,3): `row-col` is 0 for both → same ↘ diagonal, they attack. (1,2) and (2,0): sums 3 and 2, differences −1 and 2 → no shared line, safe.

```cpp
int n; vector<bool> col, diag1 /*row+col*/, diag2 /*row-col+n*/; int count = 0;
void solve(int row) {
    if (row == n) { ++count; return; }        // placed all rows
    for (int c = 0; c < n; ++c) {
        if (col[c] || diag1[row+c] || diag2[row-c+n]) continue;   // O(1) attack check
        col[c] = diag1[row+c] = diag2[row-c+n] = true;            // place
        solve(row + 1);
        col[c] = diag1[row+c] = diag2[row-c+n] = false;           // UNDO
    }
}
// sizes: col has n entries, diag1 and diag2 have 2n-1 (index range 0 .. 2n-2)
```

The make → recurse → undo bracket now sets and clears **three** flags — same skeleton as always, just a richer state. For the "return all boards" variant, also keep a `vector<int> pos` of chosen columns and render it at the base case.

**Complexity.** Roughly $O(n!)$ branches — row 0 has $n$ column options, and each placed queen prunes columns and diagonals for the rows below, shrinking the fan-out level by level. Space is $O(n)$ for the flag arrays and recursion depth.

**What generalizes.** "Encode each constraint as an O(1)-checkable index" is the transferable skill: Sudoku uses the same move with row/column/box sets, and many placement OAs reduce to *pick a slot per level + constant-time conflict sets*. Internalize `row+col` and `row-col` — they come up verbatim.
